The 7-30 Waters cartridge is a wildcat cartridge developed by author Ken Waters in 1976 to give better performance to lever action rifle shooters than the parent .30-30 Winchester cartridge, by providing a higher velocity and flatter trajectory with a smaller, lighter bullet. Duracoat Process:
The Entire rifle, all magazines, and all hardware were stripped down to individual parts. All parts were then hand prepped, and Duracoated in "Woodland Tan SL" (Gas Block Assembly, Flash Suppressor, and barrel were finished in Duraheat, same color.)

2 layers of "Matte Clear SL" were added to entire assembled rifle (Gas Block Assembly, Barrel, and Flash Suppressor finished in "Matte Clear" Duraheat)
The rifle was then left alone for 6 weeks to allow full curing of Duracoat & Duraheat.
This process was professionally performed by a military armorer with more than 2 years of professional Duracoating experience.
